<br>
I believe that humans long ago definetly needed religion. It was to explain the unexplained. Creation stories I believe are one of the major reasons for religions to form epitomised by the major role they play today in all of the worlds major religions.<br>
Religion provided comfort to people. It also provided people with a means to meet each other, to share for a common good and a basis on which to lead a good life. Values taken from religious teachings are what almost all countries use to base their laws on. Thou shalt not steal etc.<br>
In that light, I see religion as a good and usefull thing that has played a major role in bringing humankind to where it is today.<br>
<br>
In the modern world however, as you have rightly questioned, its coming under strain. Religion is so enveloping that it in effect can be held responsibile for almost everything that goes wrong in the world. Crime, death and war are atributed to it. Hate inspired wrongs are carried out in the name of religion. And this is exactly how I feel it is. Because the context is so overwhelming, so huge, and so inescapeably complex - I think that it has acquired a bad press. People may carry out crimes in the name of religion, but it is never religion that inspires them. It's simply and excuse. A justification. <br>
<br>
On the issues of belief. Again it is justification that requires the need for a proof of God. Why does their need to be proof? And isn't the fact that it can't proved enough of a reason for religion to exist in the first place? If we could prove there was a God, religion would die solely because the realisation of its existance would render it obsolete.<br>
<br>
You see, I quite agree with the symptoms you put forward. It seems absurd that we are forcing feeding material to our chilren which we know dont serve any sort of purpose in a literal meaning. It's quite strange that we are so intent on mixing science (the unrepenting need for answers) with a subject matter that asks more questions without ever really answering any questions.<br>
<br>
I think religion is misunderstood at best, and manipulated perhaps at worst. Many people benefit falsely perhaps even evilly(is that a word?) from religion and the blind devotion that it may entail. But many more benefit through a spiritual way that adds so much to their daily lives, and to the common good of them all.<br>
<br>
It's not all about whats on the surface.<br>
